hose solutions require expanding expressions using the distributive property and collecting like terms.'), ('1363', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.EE.C.8', '2', null, null, null, 'Analyze and solve pairs of simultaneous linear equations.'), ('1364', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.EE.C.8a', '2', null, null, null, 'Understand that solutions to a system of two linear equations in two variables correspond to points of intersection of their graphs, because points of intersection satisfy both equations simultaneously.'), ('1365', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.EE.C.8b', '2', null, null, null, 'Solve systems of two linear equations in two variables algebraically, and estimate solutions by graphing the equations. Solve simple cases by inspection.'), ('1366', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.EE.C.8c', '2', null, null, null, 'Solve real-world and mathematical problems leading to two linear equations in two variables.'), ('1367', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.F.A', '2', null, null, null, 'Define, evaluate, and compare functions.'), ('1368', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.F.A.1', '2', null, null, null, 'Understand that a function is a rule that assigns to each input exactly one output. The graph of a function is the set of ordered pairs consisting of an input and the corresponding output.'), ('1369', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.F.A.2', '2', null, null, null, 'Compare properties of two functions each represented in a different way (algebraically, graphically, numerically in tables, or by verbal descriptions).'), ('1370', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.F.A.3', '2', null, null, null, 'Interpret the equation y = mx + b as defining a linear function, whose graph is a straight line; give examples of functions that are not linear.'), ('1371', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.F.B', '2', null, null, null, 'Use functions to model relationships between quantities.'), ('1372', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.F.B.4', '2', null, null, null, 'Construct a function to model a linear relationship between two quantities. Determine the rate of change and initial value of the function from a description of a relationship or from two (x, y) values, including reading these from a table or from a graph'), ('1373', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.F.B.5', '2', null, null, null, 'Describe qualitatively the functional relationship between two quantities by analyzing a graph (e.g., where the function is increasing or decreasing, linear or nonlinear). Sketch a graph that exhibits the qualitative features of a function that has been d'), ('1374', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.G.A', '2', null, null, null, 'Understand congruence and similarity using physical models, transparencies, or geometry software.'), ('1375', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.G.A.1', '2', null, null, null, 'Verify experimentally the properties of rotations, reflections, and translations:'), ('1376', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.G.A.1a', '2', null, null, null, 'Lines are taken to lines, and line segments to line segments of the same length.'), ('1377', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.G.A.1b', '2', null, null, null, 'Angles are taken to angles of the same measure.'), ('1378', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.G.A.1c', '2', null, null, null, 'Parallel lines are taken to parallel lines.'), ('1379', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.G.A.2', '2', null, null, null, 'Understand that a two-dimensional figure is congruent to another if the second can be obtained from the first by a sequence of rotations, reflections, and translations; given two congruent figures, describe a sequence that exhibits the congruence between '), ('1380', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.G.A.3', '2', null, null, null, 'Describe the effect of dilations, translations, rotations, and reflections on two-dimensional figures using coordinates.'), ('1381', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.G.A.4', '2', null, null, null, 'Understand that a two-dimensional figure is similar to another if the second can be obtained from the first by a sequence of rotations, reflections, translations, and dilations; given two similar two-dimensional figures, describe a sequence that exhibits '), ('1382', 'CCSS.Math.Content.8.G.A.5', '2', null, null, null, 'Us